fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let C\xrightarrow {F} D be a functor with C small and D
complete. Then there is an equalizer diagram





    \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb}
  \usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
  \usetikzlibrary{calc}
  \usetikzlibrary{matrix}
  \usetikzlibrary{decorations.markings}

  \tikzset{
    % basics
    square/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=4},
    triangle/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=3},
  }

  \tikzset{
    % string diagrams
    state/.style={triangle, shape border rotate=180, anchor=north},
    costate/.style={triangle, anchor=south},
    morphism/.style={draw, rectangle},
    over/.style={
      draw=white,
      double=black,
      % default is .4pt
      line width=1.2pt,
      double distance=.4pt,
      text=black
    },
  }

  \tikzset{ 
    % tables
    % https://tikz.net/tikz-table/
    table/.style={
        matrix of nodes,
        row sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        column sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        nodes={
            rectangle,
            draw=black,
            align=center
        },
        minimum height=1.5em,
        text depth=0.5ex,
        text height=2ex,
        nodes in empty cells,
%%
        every even row/.style={
            nodes={fill=gray!20}
        },
        column 1/.style={
            nodes={font=\bfseries}
        },
        row 1/.style={
            nodes={
                fill=black,
                text=white,
                font=\bfseries
            }
        }
    }
  }


    \begin {tikzcd}
    & & Fy
    \\
    Fc\ar [r, hook] &
    \displaystyle \prod _{c\xrightarrow {j} x} (F\Pi  j = Fx)\ar [r, shift left=.2em, dashed]\ar [r, shift
    right=.2em, dashed]\ar [ur, "\pi _{kj}"]\ar [d, "\pi _j"'] &
    \displaystyle \prod _{c\xrightarrow {j} x\xrightarrow {k} y} (F\Pi  (kj) = Fy)\ar [u, "\pi _{kj}"']\ar [d, "\pi _{kj}"]\makebox [0pt][l]{.} \\
    & Fx\ar [r, "Fk"'] & Fy
    \end {tikzcd}

Dually, for D cocomplete, there is a coequalizer diagram 




    \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb}
  \usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
  \usetikzlibrary{calc}
  \usetikzlibrary{matrix}
